06161nam a22008415i 9781782388265DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t19991999nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97817823882657 a10.1515/97817823882652doi  a(DE-B1597)637344  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aE183.8.A8b.F766 1999 7aHIS0270902bisacsh00aFrom World War to Waldheim :bCulture and Politics in Austria and the United States /ced. by David F. Good, Ruth Wodak. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[1999] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAustrian and Habsburg Studies ;v200tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tTHE SOUND OF FORGETTING MEETS THE UNITED STATES OF AMNESIA -- tPart One. THE POLITICS OF AUSTRIAN-AMERICAN RELATIONS -- tChapter 1. AMERICAN ATTITUDES TOWARD AUSTRIA AND AUSTRIAN-GERMAN RELATIONS SINCE 1945 -- tChapter 2. BRUNO KREISKY’S PERCEPTIONS OF THE UNITED STATES -- tChapter 3. BITBURG, WALDHEIM, AND THE POLITICS OF REMEMBERING AND FORGETTING -- tPart Two. THE AUSTRIAN IMPACT ON AMERICAN CULTURE -- tChapter 4. MASS EMIGRATION AND INTELLECTUAL EXILE FROM NATIONAL SOCIALISM -- tChapter 5. THE INFLUENCE OF AUSTRIAN ÉMIGRÉS ON THE DEVELOPMENT AND EXPANSION OF PSYCHOANALYSIS IN THE UNITED STATES AFTER 1945 -- tChapter 6. HEIMAT HOLLYWOOD -- tPart Three. AMERICA AND AUSTRIAN POLITICAL CULTURE -- tChapter 7. ROBERTWISE’S THE SOUND OF MUSIC AND THE “DENAZIFICATION” OF AUSTRIA IN AMERICAN CINEMA -- tChapter 8. POLITICAL CULTURE AND THE ABORTION CONFLICT -- tChapter 9. AMERICANIZATION, CULTURAL CHANGE, AND AUSTRIAN IDENTITY -- tLIST OF CONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe growing internationalization of the world poses a fundamental question, i.e., through what mechanisms does culture diffuse across political boundaries and what is the role of politics in shaping this diffusion? This volume offers some answers through the case study of the relationship between two quite different states during the Cold War era - Austria, a small neutral country, and the United States, the reigning superpower. The authors challenge naive notions of cultural diffusion that posit the submission of small "peripheral" areas to the dictates of hegemonic powers at the "core." "Americanization" has no doubt taken place since 1945; however, local forces crucially shaped this process, and Austrian elites enjoyed considerable leeway in pursuing "Austrian" political objectives. On the other hand, with the expulsion of Vienna's cultural and intellectual elite after the Anschluß, the United States, more than any othercountry, became heir to the rich cultural legacy of "Vienna 1900," which profoundly shaped politics and culture in both its "high" and popular forms in postwar America. The relationship climaxed and came full circle with the unfolding of the Waldheim affair, which forced Americans and Austrians to reinterpret the meaning of the Nazi era for their own history in a confrontation with the "other."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aCulture diffusionzAustria. 0aCulture diffusionzUnited States. 0aNational socialismxPsychological aspects. 0aPolitical culturezAustria. 0aPolitical culturezUnited States. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War I.2bisacsh1 aBunzl, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGood, David F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGood, David F., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHandlbauer, Bernhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLarkey, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMesner, Maria